  "prompt": "What is the latent heat of a fusion?",
  "response": "Latent heat of fusion is the amount of energy required to change a substance from the solid phase to the liquid phase at its melting point, without changing its temperature. This energy is needed to overcome the forces holding the solid structure together. The latent heat of fusion is typically expressed in units of energy per mass, such as joules per gram (J/g) or kilojoules per kilogram (kJ/kg).\n\nFor example:\n- The latent heat of fusion for water is approximately 334 J/g or 334 kJ/kg.\n",
